![Reports of Russian military moving across the border into Ukraine caused a
Twitter avalanche. Image from Twitter.](https://globalvoicesonline.org/wp-
content/uploads/2014/08/russia-ukraine-invasion-hashtag.jpg)

Reports of Russian military moving across the border into Ukraine caused a
Twitter avalanche. Image from Twitter.

On Wednesday Russia expanded its push across the Ukrainian border, apparently
sending troops and armor into the town of Novoazovsk in Donetsk region, in
what the media [described as a stealth
invasion](http://www.nytimes.com/2014/08/28/world/europe/ukraine-russia-
novoazovsk-
crimea.html?hp&action=click&pgtype=Homepage&version=LedeSumLargeMedia&module=a-lede-
package-region&region=top-news&WT.nav=top-news&_r=1). Ukrainian social media
users replied with thousands of posts, calling the world's attention to the
alarming news.

As the first reports of Russian troops taking over new frontiers along the
border appeared, Twitter and other social networks started sounding the alarm
as users tried to decide how to raise awareness of the incursion. The
situation clearly called for a hashtag, and one enterprising Belarusian user
[@belamova](https://twitter.com/belamova/) came up with just the thing:

> Нужна 1000 ретвитов, чтобы вывести хештег о вторжении Рашки в мировые тренды
> [#RussiainvadedUkraine](https://twitter.com/hashtag/RussiainvadedUkraine?src=hash)
>
> — РБ головного мозга (@belamova) [August 27,
> 2014](https://twitter.com/belamova/statuses/504708551894659072)

> We need 1000 retweets to get the hashtag about Russia's invasion into the
> world trends #RussiainvadedUkraine

The hashtag
[#RussiainvadedUkraine](https://twitter.com/search?f=realtime&q=%23RussiainvadedUkraine&src=typd)
and its companion phrases spread like wildfire, with users [providing
directions](https://twitter.com/krivorozhanin_/statuses/504728111863590912)
for making them go viral to reach both Russian-speaking and Western audiences:

> Пишем твиты на иностранных языках с хэштэгами
> [#UkraineUnderAttack](https://twitter.com/hashtag/UkraineUnderAttack?src=hash)
> [#RussiainvadedUkraine](https://twitter.com/hashtag/RussiainvadedUkraine?src=hash)
> MAX RT
>
> — Хуёвый Кривой Рог (@krivorozhanin_) [August 27,
> 2014](https://twitter.com/krivorozhanin_/statuses/504728111863590912)

> Let's write tweets in foreign languages with hashtags #UkraineUnderAttack
> #RussiainvadedUkraine. MAX RT

The call to action was clearly taken up by Ukrainians on Twitter—in the first
hour after the hashtag
[#RussiainvadedUkraine](https://twitter.com/search?f=realtime&q=%23RussiainvadedUkraine&src=typd)
was born, it racked up over 100 thousand tweets and retweets, [topping 350
thousand](http://topsy.com/s?q=%23RussiainvadedUkraine&window=d) tweets later
in the day. On Russian social network VKontakte, 3-5 posts tagged with the
same hashtag [popped up every
second](http://watcher.com.ua/2014/08/27/schosekundy-u-vkontakte-
zyavlyayetsya-3-5-novyh-zapysy-pro-ukraineunderattack-ta-
russiainvadedukraine/) at the height of the flashmob. Netizens posted in
Russian, Ukrainian, English and other languages, addressed various officials
and international organizations, and of course, shared evocative art in order
to draw attention.

> HELP UKRAINE NOW
> [#UkraineUnderAttack](https://twitter.com/hashtag/UkraineUnderAttack?src=hash)
> [#RussiainvadedUkraine](https://twitter.com/hashtag/RussiainvadedUkraine?src=hash)
> [pic.twitter.com/47ypFLklrF](http://t.co/47ypFLklrF)
>
> — Поміркований бандера (@mr_untitle) [August 27,
> 2014](https://twitter.com/mr_untitle/statuses/504718671990636544)

>
> [#russiainvadesukraine](https://twitter.com/hashtag/russiainvadesukraine?src=hash)
> [pic.twitter.com/Hr6pqKZ95h](http://t.co/Hr6pqKZ95h)
>
> — Civic Sector (@maidan_go) [August 27,
> 2014](https://twitter.com/maidan_go/statuses/504743596432834561)

Along with regular users, official accounts also joined the hashtag flashmob,
including the Ukrainian [Ministry of Foreign
Affairs](https://twitter.com/MFA_Ukraine/):

>
> [#UkraineUnderAttack](https://twitter.com/hashtag/UkraineUnderAttack?src=hash)
> [#RussiaInvadedUkraine](https://twitter.com/hashtag/RussiaInvadedUkraine?src=hash)
> RT PLZ [pic.twitter.com/KMM9ezqAfv](http://t.co/KMM9ezqAfv)
>
> — MFA of Ukraine (@MFA_Ukraine) [August 27,
> 2014](https://twitter.com/MFA_Ukraine/statuses/504734047030239232)

Since the Ministry's tweet only contained the hashtags, some users, like
KyivPost journalist [Christopher Miller](https://twitter.com/ChristopherJM/),
wondered at how to interpret the message.

> Is this the [#Ukraine](https://twitter.com/hashtag/Ukraine?src=hash)
> government's official announcement of a
> [#Russia](https://twitter.com/hashtag/Russia?src=hash) invasion, with
> hashtags? <https://t.co/rH0JQkjkfU>
>
> — Christopher Miller (@ChristopherJM) [August 27,
> 2014](https://twitter.com/ChristopherJM/statuses/504742431619690497)

With news of the invasion spreading, the hashtag
[#RussiainvadedUkraine](https://twitter.com/search?f=realtime&q=%23RussiainvadedUkraine&src=typd)
was soon trending in Ukraine, and then went to the top of world Twitter
trends, as seen in this [screenshot posted to
Twitter](https://twitter.com/stabilizec/statuses/504740047321853952).

>
> [#UkraineUnderAttack](https://twitter.com/hashtag/UkraineUnderAttack?src=hash)
> [#RussiainvadedUkraine](https://twitter.com/hashtag/RussiainvadedUkraine?src=hash)
> [#UkraineUnderAttack](https://twitter.com/hashtag/UkraineUnderAttack?src=hash)
> [#RussiainvadedUkraine](https://twitter.com/hashtag/RussiainvadedUkraine?src=hash)
> [#UkraineUnderAttack](https://twitter.com/hashtag/UkraineUnderAttack?src=hash)
> [pic.twitter.com/KGad3iPjq0](http://t.co/KGad3iPjq0)
>
> — Дно где-то рядом (@stabilizec) [August 27,
> 2014](https://twitter.com/stabilizec/statuses/504740047321853952)

Although most of the tweets protesting Russia's border breach came from
Ukrainians, some Russian social media users also joined the wave of outrage. A
tweet by user [Dmitry Monakhov](https://twitter.com/dmtrmon/), in which he
announced he was going to protest Kremlin's actions on Manezhnaya square in
Moscow, collected over 1700 retweets.

> Я россиянин. Не быдло. Не убийца. И не оккупант. Мне стыдно что Путин мой
> президент. В 9.00 я иду на манежку против войны.
>
> — Dmitry Monakhov (@dmtrmon) [August 27,
> 2014](https://twitter.com/dmtrmon/statuses/504730358756425729)

> I am Russian. I am not a thug. I am not a killer. And not an occupant. I am
> ashamed to have Putin as my president. At 9:00 I am going to Manezhnaya
> [square] to stand against war.

Monakhov's tweet was at least in part made viral by a
[retweet](https://twitter.com/mefimus/statuses/504753096070008832) from
[Mustafa Nayyem](https://twitter.com/mefimus/), a Ukrainian-Afghani journalist
credited with catalyzing the Euromaidan protests in November of last year with
a Facebook post.

> RT! Давайте поможем нашим российским коллегам.
> [@dmtrmon](https://twitter.com/dmtrmon)
> [pic.twitter.com/J9HSZtVJfe](http://t.co/J9HSZtVJfe)
>
> — Mustafa Nayyem (@mefimus) [August 27,
> 2014](https://twitter.com/mefimus/statuses/504753096070008832)

> RT! Let's help our Russian colleagues.

Other users in the RuNet, like opposition activist [Ruslan
Levyev](https://twitter.com/RuslanLeviev/), also called Russians to come out
and protest to their city's central square.

> Никакого «назначенного времени» и места нет! Это бессрочная акция, выходите
> когда можете и где можете! Ближе к центру. Манежка, Красная
>
> — Руслан Левиев (@RuslanLeviev) [August 27,
> 2014](https://twitter.com/RuslanLeviev/statuses/504757985726701568)

> There's no “appointed time” or place! This is an action with no deadline,
> come out when you can and where you can! Closer to the city center.
> Manezhnaya [square], Red [square].

The hashtag storm on Twitter and other social networks undoubtedly caught the
attention of Ukrainian and Western media and officials, and solicited
expressions of solidarity among Russians. It is unclear if it results in any
discernible action on the part of Ukrainian authorities or new sanctions for
Russia from the West. Will the US and EU continue to simply be “deeply
concerned”? As the situation escalates, Ukrainians turn to social networks to
campaign for some kind of reaction, but the real answers might be harder to
come by than a spot in the Twitter world trends.

